1
00:00:01,195 --> 00:00:09,871
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasah.

2
00:00:11,914 --> 00:00:20,571
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasah.

3
00:00:22,998 --> 00:00:39,048
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble, and fully self-enlightened one.

4
00:00:41,442 --> 00:00:44,965
Over the past couple of days, we've concentrated on suffering.

5
00:00:46,066 --> 00:00:51,371
Not simply how physical and mental pain cause suffering, but how pleasure does so.

6
00:00:52,451 --> 00:00:54,274
Now, see how I phrased that?

7
00:00:55,134 --> 00:00:55,936
It's wrong, isn't it?

8
00:00:56,957 --> 00:01:03,703
Nothing causes us to suffer, but the relationship we have to what we experience.

9
00:01:03,722 --> 00:01:11,010
In other words, it's not pain that is the primary cause of our suffering, but our aversion to it, our fear of it,

10
00:01:12,560 --> 00:01:18,840
Pleasures and joy do not cause suffering, but our indulgence and dependence on them does.

11
00:01:21,081 --> 00:01:23,545
We have to be very careful how we use language.

12
00:01:24,506 --> 00:01:28,290
In what we say, how we say, is contained our view of things.

13
00:01:29,671 --> 00:01:39,903
So just by picking ourselves up on a simple slip such as, this headache is unbearable, I can't stand these people, these politicians make me sick.

14
00:01:41,225 --> 00:01:46,031
Just by catching the way we talk about things and people, we can correct our view.

15
00:01:46,691 --> 00:01:48,353
Eventually, the penny will drop.

16
00:01:48,954 --> 00:01:50,716
There will be a change of heart.

17
00:01:53,700 --> 00:01:59,552
Now there's an expression which tells us how things happen at the psychological and spiritual level.

18
00:02:00,593 --> 00:02:02,897
It's not good enough to understand the Dharma.

19
00:02:03,698 --> 00:02:06,403
It's not even good enough to be convinced of the Dharma.

20
00:02:07,186 --> 00:02:14,038
We have to work so that the correct view, the Dharma, begins to bring a change of heart.

21
00:02:14,018 --> 00:02:20,812
That's why in the Eightfold Path, after the number one, Right View, there comes Right Attitude.

22
00:02:21,754 --> 00:02:26,425
Then only does Right Speech, Right Action and Right Livelihood follow.

23
00:02:28,143 --> 00:02:31,586
But we need to start somewhere, and that's to correct our view.

24
00:02:32,448 --> 00:02:38,275
Now the Buddha tells us that we have three fundamental delusions about the way things really are.

25
00:02:39,256 --> 00:02:40,897
He puts it to us directly.

26
00:02:41,699 --> 00:02:42,399
No fudging.

27
00:02:42,919 --> 00:02:44,361
This is the way it is.

28
00:02:46,264 --> 00:02:55,854
He declares that not seeing the three characteristics of existence clearly causes our lives to be unsatisfactory, if not downright unbearable.

29
00:02:57,235 --> 00:03:07,294
The first two concern everything that has existence, and one pertains only to sentient beings, and that includes us, human beings.

30
00:03:08,899 --> 00:03:16,914
These three characteristics are impermanence, unsatisfactoriness, and not-self or insubstantiality.

31
00:03:18,312 --> 00:03:21,379
The unsatisfactoriness is this suffering we create.

32
00:03:21,741 --> 00:03:22,543
That's dukkha.

33
00:03:23,504 --> 00:03:26,432
Dukkha means in itself a hard place.

34
00:03:27,294 --> 00:03:27,856
That's life.

35
00:03:28,478 --> 00:03:32,288
As the comedian said, life's hard and then you die.

36
00:03:33,854 --> 00:03:37,340
Again, translating from other languages never quite makes it.

37
00:03:38,421 --> 00:03:41,647
And Dukkha has such a breadth of meaning, books are written about it.

38
00:03:42,590 --> 00:03:54,090
In fact, if we take the Buddha's own pithy description of his teachings, I teach only Dukkha and the end of Dukkha, it really does become the biggest word in the Buddha Dhamma.

39
00:03:56,027 --> 00:04:04,175
In the past it was translated as suffering, but that's the wild end, most now translated as unsatisfactoriness.

40
00:04:05,116 --> 00:04:14,746
It's the lack of comfort, the lack of contentment, always wanting something, and as one writer puts it, just the lack.

41
00:04:15,847 --> 00:04:21,151
And this is what we've been pondering when we've talked of the hindrances and the problems of pleasure.

42
00:04:23,334 --> 00:04:25,596
Now it's the turn to look at impermanence.

43
00:04:26,605 --> 00:04:37,714
Paradoxically, if there's one unchanging truth about the material and individual mental universes, it's that everything, without exception, is in a process of change.

44
00:04:39,516 --> 00:04:44,161
I read an excellent book on the cosmos, on galaxies and super-galaxies.

45
00:04:45,562 --> 00:04:50,266
Astronomers estimate at least 100 billion galaxies, 100 billion!

46
00:04:51,288 --> 00:04:55,211
And some of these galaxies have millions, if not billions, of stars.

47
00:04:56,237 --> 00:04:57,721
The pictures of them are stunning.

48
00:04:57,761 --> 00:05:01,610
These colossi spinning in the emptiness of space.

49
00:05:02,391 --> 00:05:05,377
Huge vortices of unimaginable energy.

50
00:05:06,019 --> 00:05:08,223
Stars being formed, others exploding.

51
00:05:08,886 --> 00:05:14,398
Black holes with inverted energy that sucks everything into them from light years away.

52
00:05:14,377 --> 00:05:16,822
It's so big, it's beyond fantasy.

53
00:05:17,182 --> 00:05:20,569
The mind, well, my mind, just can't grasp it.

54
00:05:21,230 --> 00:05:22,952
I get lost after a few stars.

55
00:05:23,754 --> 00:05:29,023
I look up at the night sky and I simply cannot mentally perceive what's going on.

56
00:05:29,504 --> 00:05:31,468
It's too vast, too overwhelming.

57
00:05:32,569 --> 00:05:36,976
And it's all, all of it, in a state of ferocious change.

58
00:05:38,762 --> 00:05:43,192
Coming down to earth, getting my feet back on the ground, I find the same.

59
00:05:43,232 --> 00:05:51,168
The ever-changing seasons, the appearance of flowers in spring, their bloom in summer, their disappearance in autumn.

60
00:05:52,177 --> 00:06:00,769
The leaves bright yellow-green in spring, deep green in summer, mellow brown in autumn, and then just a load of litter.

61
00:06:02,192 --> 00:06:05,216
The tireless sun, rising and setting every day.

62
00:06:05,257 --> 00:06:09,242
The snow, the ice, the sleet, the slush, the rain.

63
00:06:10,384 --> 00:06:14,690
There's a pattern to it all, but it's hidden, as it were, within change.

64
00:06:15,572 --> 00:06:19,737
There are laws governing change, but there's always change.

65
00:06:21,136 --> 00:06:22,257
and human society.

66
00:06:23,139 --> 00:06:24,382
Just look at human history.

67
00:06:25,144 --> 00:06:31,817
Look at human progress, or perhaps the better word is progression, throughout the comparatively short time we've been here.

68
00:06:32,778 --> 00:06:33,781
Constantly changing.

69
00:06:34,423 --> 00:06:36,726
A restlessness, war and peace.

70
00:06:37,449 --> 00:06:40,173
The growth and collapse of huge civilisations.

71
00:06:41,925 --> 00:06:43,427
Coming down to the Manusii.

72
00:06:44,348 --> 00:06:47,031
The Daily News with its constant flow of changes.

73
00:06:47,471 --> 00:06:49,952
Businesses starting, businesses flopping.

74
00:06:50,694 --> 00:06:53,096
Politicians doing this, undoing that.

75
00:06:53,997 --> 00:06:55,778
Unions, workers, voluntary bodies.

76
00:06:55,999 --> 00:06:57,339
The list is legion.

77
00:06:58,040 --> 00:07:00,783
People doing things, changing things.

78
00:07:01,283 --> 00:07:03,805
Sometimes unskillfully, sometimes skillfully.

79
00:07:04,125 --> 00:07:05,908
But nothing can be left alone.

80
00:07:06,689 --> 00:07:10,531
Someone's always around to change things.

81
00:07:10,512 --> 00:07:14,475
Everyone everywhere, it seems, has to be doing something.

82
00:07:16,519 --> 00:07:18,461
Finally, we close in on ourselves.

83
00:07:19,021 --> 00:07:19,822
And what do we find?

84
00:07:20,302 --> 00:07:20,723
Change.

85
00:07:21,644 --> 00:07:26,870
We change our dwellings, our friends, our jobs, sometimes our spouses and partners.

86
00:07:27,990 --> 00:07:29,012
Children come and go.

87
00:07:29,072 --> 00:07:32,677
And as we progress through life, we change inside.

88
00:07:33,437 --> 00:07:36,620
Things happen to us that change the way we see things.

89
00:07:36,904 --> 00:07:43,276
Just think how much we've changed since we were born, since we were just a bundle of gurgling, screaming flesh.

90
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:45,682
And our bodies.

91
00:07:46,624 --> 00:07:52,154
Every seven years, some books say five, every single atom in the body has been replaced.

92
00:07:53,437 --> 00:07:58,086
Next time you look in the mirror, remind yourself you didn't have that face seven years ago.

93
00:07:59,634 --> 00:08:02,800
and the different parts of the body are changing at different rates.

94
00:08:03,903 --> 00:08:07,350
We'd live a long time if our longevity was measured by our bones.

95
00:08:08,492 --> 00:08:13,382
Sometimes the liver grows old, faster than the heart, and we die of some liver disease.

96
00:08:14,605 --> 00:08:17,711
Sometimes it's the heart, or the lungs, or the brain.

97
00:08:18,485 --> 00:08:24,113
A lot depends on how we've treated the body, but for the most part it seems to depend on our genetic makeup.

98
00:08:25,214 --> 00:08:27,738
In my own family, we all seem to die of strokes.

99
00:08:28,880 --> 00:08:30,423
I only know of one case of cancer.

100
00:08:31,444 --> 00:08:34,249
I have a friend whose family all die of cancer, and early, too.

101
00:08:35,770 --> 00:08:45,605
But whatever way we go, go we must, because death is the corollary of birth, and without birth and death, there's no change.

102
00:08:48,015 --> 00:08:54,224
Now the upside of change is this birthing, these beginnings, the newness, the creativity.

103
00:08:55,765 --> 00:09:02,313
When we look at nature we learn that over the ages she has created masses of variations in plant and animal life.

104
00:09:03,615 --> 00:09:07,220
It's said that 99% of all species have become extinct.

105
00:09:08,380 --> 00:09:12,726
Now this seems a very high figure but it gives an idea of how creative nature is.

106
00:09:14,509 --> 00:09:17,753
But it couldn't create anything new if the old didn't die.

107
00:09:19,284 --> 00:09:26,437
We as human beings love to concentrate on the new, on the present fashion, the new song, the new celebrity.

108
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:28,687
It's exciting and wonderful.

109
00:09:29,798 --> 00:09:35,224
We're always on the lookout for the new dish, the new film, the new clothes.

110
00:09:35,244 --> 00:09:39,028
The whole of our society is geared to the creation of the new.

111
00:09:40,068 --> 00:09:44,874
The whole of industry is about producing, something new, upgrading.

112
00:09:45,916 --> 00:09:52,201
Whether it be a new source of energy, a new gadget, a new drug, a new computer game, a new perfume.

113
00:09:53,583 --> 00:09:57,307
So long as we concentrate on the new, we feel happy.

114
00:09:58,350 --> 00:10:02,437
for in our understanding, new seems to always mean good.

115
00:10:04,780 --> 00:10:18,503
Individually, we concentrate on what we're going to do tomorrow, at the weekend, next week, next year, where I want to be in ten years' time, how I shall spend my retirement.

116
00:10:19,697 --> 00:10:21,660
Our delusion demands we look ahead.

117
00:10:22,361 --> 00:10:23,663
We plan for the future.

118
00:10:24,644 --> 00:10:26,307
And for the most part, it's exciting.

119
00:10:27,148 --> 00:10:33,116
It's so exciting that we don't see that things are disappearing, that things die out.

120
00:10:33,837 --> 00:10:38,524
We don't notice that to create something new, we have to get rid of something old.

121
00:10:39,826 --> 00:10:42,549
We become blind to the downside of change.

122
00:10:45,196 --> 00:10:47,938
Now self cannot live long in the present.

123
00:10:49,100 --> 00:10:53,485
The present moment is death to self unless it presumes a next moment.

124
00:10:55,527 --> 00:10:57,889
Suddenly something happens that pulls us up short.

125
00:10:58,929 --> 00:11:00,692
I woke up one morning and brushed my teeth.

126
00:11:01,852 --> 00:11:02,754
All my teeth were there.

127
00:11:03,995 --> 00:11:05,496
At breakfast I bit into an apple.

128
00:11:06,457 --> 00:11:09,721
There was a snap, a crack, a front tooth fell out.

129
00:11:10,782 --> 00:11:11,423
Just like that.

130
00:11:12,381 --> 00:11:15,746
Where there had been a tooth, there was now no tooth.

131
00:11:17,730 --> 00:11:19,493
Life can sometimes be like that, can't it?

132
00:11:20,455 --> 00:11:26,384
You wake up one morning feeling a little off, and after examinations and tests, you're given six weeks to live.

133
00:11:27,546 --> 00:11:30,389
You step out on the road, and bang, you're dead.

134
00:11:32,041 --> 00:11:37,730
There was an elderly woman got on the same plane as I did from Colombo, Sri Lanka, to London.

135
00:11:38,551 --> 00:11:41,535
We were half an hour into the flight and she began to fret.

136
00:11:42,878 --> 00:11:45,221
She had asthma and other complications, it seems.

137
00:11:46,722 --> 00:11:49,447
She was probably planning to spend Easter with her family.

138
00:11:50,929 --> 00:11:51,831
She was dead in an hour.

139
00:11:53,653 --> 00:11:58,100
A good acquaintance of mine got drunk one night and went down to the cellar to get more booze.

140
00:11:58,981 --> 00:11:59,482
He slipped.

141
00:12:00,576 --> 00:12:03,360
He's now in Mandeville Hospital, paralysed from the neck down.

142
00:12:05,462 --> 00:12:10,148
When such things happen around us, it's a shock, a real shock.

143
00:12:10,168 --> 00:12:12,010
When it happens to us, it's a trauma.

144
00:12:13,192 --> 00:12:13,491
Why?

145
00:12:14,452 --> 00:12:15,934
Why should we be shocked?

146
00:12:16,936 --> 00:12:20,299
Why should we be traumatised by events that are happening all the time?

147
00:12:21,481 --> 00:12:25,326
Isn't it because we don't care to look at the downside of impermanence?

148
00:12:26,047 --> 00:12:27,629
We don't want to look at it.

149
00:12:27,649 --> 00:12:28,389
It's scary.

150
00:12:29,533 --> 00:12:32,899
Yet with the appearance of the new, the old has died.

151
00:12:35,302 --> 00:12:43,855
The Buddha tells us that this is one of the great weaknesses of self, that level of consciousness which identifies with the body and the personality.

152
00:12:44,996 --> 00:12:47,921
It's very frightened by death, death in all its forms.

153
00:12:48,883 --> 00:12:52,567
The mini-death of my tooth, the mega-death of my body.

154
00:12:53,850 --> 00:12:58,056
If I am that, what happens to me when that disappears?

155
00:12:59,149 --> 00:13:01,231
The thought is too horrible to contemplate.

156
00:13:02,192 --> 00:13:03,894
It's got to mean annihilation.

157
00:13:05,636 --> 00:13:08,581
If I am the body, then I'm nothing when it's dead.

158
00:13:09,902 --> 00:13:23,457
If I am the personality, and that can only exist in a body, in a brain, within a given culture, then when the body dies, everything I've come to know as me, everything I am, evaporates, dissolves.

159
00:13:24,139 --> 00:13:24,918
There's nothing left.

160
00:13:26,160 --> 00:13:28,043
Death is an utter annihilation.

161
00:13:30,503 --> 00:13:32,769
Now such thoughts can definitely make us gloomy.

162
00:13:33,490 --> 00:13:36,357
After all, there's something utterly final about death.

163
00:13:37,080 --> 00:13:38,102
There's no coming back.

164
00:13:38,423 --> 00:13:38,865
That's it.

165
00:13:40,369 --> 00:13:45,863
When they asked how much the old rich woman had left, the lawyer said, Everything.

166
00:13:47,412 --> 00:13:53,701
When we really absorb the fact that we take nothing material with us, it can undermine our purpose for living.

167
00:13:54,481 --> 00:13:55,364
Why make an effort?

168
00:13:55,844 --> 00:13:57,907
Why bother about what sort of house I've got?

169
00:13:58,388 --> 00:13:59,349
What sort of car?

170
00:14:00,129 --> 00:14:01,152
What does it matter?

171
00:14:01,732 --> 00:14:03,054
The jolly reaper takes all.

172
00:14:04,196 --> 00:14:09,003
Not a single penny of all the billions I have are of any use to me come that moment.

173
00:14:09,904 --> 00:14:10,424
Why live?

174
00:14:12,168 --> 00:14:13,690
What about my relationships?

175
00:14:14,682 --> 00:14:18,966
How much of my happiness is dependent on being loved by someone?

176
00:14:21,008 --> 00:14:23,990
How much on being able to love someone?

177
00:14:25,251 --> 00:14:26,693
Yet what love lasts?

178
00:14:28,335 --> 00:14:34,640
Isn't there something rather sad, perhaps a little pathetic, about continuing to love someone who has died?

179
00:14:36,062 --> 00:14:36,682
Yet who doesn't?

180
00:14:39,485 --> 00:14:43,389
Meditating on death and all its implications is a tough one.

181
00:14:44,347 --> 00:14:46,850
Yet to meditate on death is known as a protection.

182
00:14:47,871 --> 00:14:49,053
What's it protecting us from?

183
00:14:50,235 --> 00:14:56,383
It's protecting us from the illusion which self loves to deceive us with, the illusion of continuity.

184
00:14:57,904 --> 00:14:59,046
Death doesn't come to me.

185
00:14:59,647 --> 00:15:02,149
Yes, I know everyone dies, but that's everyone else.

186
00:15:02,431 --> 00:15:05,134
And anyway, if I do have to, it won't be yet.

187
00:15:05,573 --> 00:15:11,621
It's too distant in the future for it to be of any importance to me, for it to have any effect on my life now.

188
00:15:13,340 --> 00:15:18,868
How many of us go to bed and remind ourselves that we may die in our sleep that very night?

189
00:15:20,269 --> 00:15:22,133
A chilling thought, yet we could.

190
00:15:23,975 --> 00:15:30,905
My most enduring teacher, Bhante Rewithadama, arrived back from a long flight and complained of something in his chest.

191
00:15:31,888 --> 00:15:33,710
The monks massaged him and he felt better.

192
00:15:34,631 --> 00:15:35,533
He died that night.

193
00:15:37,149 --> 00:15:41,034
Contemplating death, my death, gets me in touch with that fear.

194
00:15:42,197 --> 00:15:52,390
And the amount of fear I feel on the thought of death or when death approaches me or when it's my turn to die is the measure of the delusion that I live by.

195
00:15:54,193 --> 00:15:56,898
This fear is the ground emotion of self.

196
00:15:58,038 --> 00:16:02,785
Self grasps and gathers and aggrandizes to allay the feelings of anxiety.

197
00:16:03,868 --> 00:16:06,971
It builds up shoring walls against the possibility of death.

198
00:16:08,284 --> 00:16:13,254
Self fights and battles and wars to defend its territory, its possessions.

199
00:16:14,035 --> 00:16:16,500
For to lose an inch is to lose an inch of self.

200
00:16:17,221 --> 00:16:20,248
And to lose an inch of self is to suffer a mini-death.

201
00:16:21,750 --> 00:16:29,144
And when the odds are stacked against it, self runs, flees, flies in a madness, lost in a paroxysm of fear.

202
00:16:31,589 --> 00:16:33,873
How can we guard ourselves against such suffering?

203
00:16:35,235 --> 00:16:40,783
We do it by constantly chipping away at the delusions self would have us believe.

204
00:16:42,846 --> 00:16:50,138
And the delusion which comes because we don't care to observe and acknowledge impermanence is the illusion of continuity.

205
00:16:51,703 --> 00:17:02,681
Because we concentrate on the new, and the new is arising out of the old, we believe that reality is one continual flow of events happening to a static me.

206
00:17:03,783 --> 00:17:14,538
The I, the consciousness that knows what's happening, feels itself to be constant and utterly separate from the flow of change and therefore not part of it.

207
00:17:16,055 --> 00:17:23,604
The contemplation of the ever presence of death is the most potent corrective that undermines this fundamental delusion.

208
00:17:24,744 --> 00:17:26,606
It brings us back into reality.

209
00:17:27,508 --> 00:17:28,750
This is the way it is.

210
00:17:30,231 --> 00:17:32,934
Sure, fear arises, but it won't make us run.

211
00:17:34,096 --> 00:17:38,181
We see that fear is arising out of the inability to deal with reality.

212
00:17:39,410 --> 00:17:44,217
So in our meditation we look straight into the terrorizing eyes of fear.

213
00:17:45,179 --> 00:17:46,942
We investigate fear.

214
00:17:46,961 --> 00:17:48,263
We feel its sickliness.

215
00:17:49,105 --> 00:17:50,928
We sit calmly in the nausea.

216
00:17:51,909 --> 00:17:55,775
Slowly we come to feel at ease with that fearful inner environment.

217
00:17:56,836 --> 00:17:59,721
We find we can sit still in the midst of the whirlwind.

218
00:18:00,563 --> 00:18:06,632
We can find the eye where all is still and untouched by the surrounding tornado.

219
00:18:06,612 --> 00:18:11,343
Slowly we lose our fear of fear, our fear of anxiety.

220
00:18:13,268 --> 00:18:21,667
Now I ask you, if we lose our fear of fear, our fear of anxiety, what can possibly frighten us?

221
00:18:23,452 --> 00:18:29,622
That's the place we've got to work towards, being able to sit still amidst the icy winds of fear.

222
00:18:30,502 --> 00:18:32,144
Then the rest will take care of itself.

223
00:18:33,186 --> 00:18:37,413
As always, when we leave the heart alone, we find that she cures herself.

224
00:18:38,693 --> 00:18:48,448
Like any turbulence, when we stop twirling it, when we stop energizing it, it loses momentum, exhausts itself, and finally comes to a stillness.

225
00:18:49,541 --> 00:19:00,819
All we have to do is to find that aloof position of the observing within us, knowing the presenting fear and the fear of fear, and slowly all will quieten.

226
00:19:02,663 --> 00:19:07,510
In the end all fear vanishes and all possibility of fear is extinguished.

227
00:19:08,913 --> 00:19:11,297
The liberated one is fearless.

228
00:19:13,488 --> 00:19:26,368
In Buddhist iconography, this is symbolized in the abhaya posture, the posture of fearlessness, where the Buddha holds up his right hand, the palm facing us, offering us the protection of fearlessness.

229
00:19:27,991 --> 00:19:29,653
This posture we can internalize.

230
00:19:30,335 --> 00:19:38,127
We can visualize that hand between our awareness and emotions, and so protects the knowing from being swamped and hijacked.

231
00:19:39,711 --> 00:19:46,803
We can even visualize that hand before our heart and it acts as a protection against the emotional bombardment of other people.

232
00:19:49,787 --> 00:19:52,791
So, contemplating death is part of our practice.

233
00:19:53,593 --> 00:19:56,076
That's why I include it in the evening meditation.

234
00:19:57,819 --> 00:20:02,547
The spiritual reason is that it undermines the hold that self has over us.

235
00:20:03,926 --> 00:20:07,270
When the self is broken asunder, that is our liberation.

236
00:20:08,672 --> 00:20:12,497
And it's not only death we should contemplate, but sickness and aging.

237
00:20:13,498 --> 00:20:15,559
These are mini-deaths.

238
00:20:15,579 --> 00:20:18,282
The one protects us from the intoxication of health.

239
00:20:19,244 --> 00:20:24,750
That's what the Buddha calls it, intoxication, a bewilderment, an obsession with our health.

240
00:20:26,071 --> 00:20:33,681
And contemplating aging lifts us out of the intoxication, the bewilderment, the desire constantly to be youthful

241
00:20:35,315 --> 00:20:39,270
We always want to be young, somewhere between our twenties and early thirties.

242
00:20:40,415 --> 00:20:41,780
But time doesn't care for that.

243
00:20:44,545 --> 00:20:47,691
Now the contemplation of death should be brought into everything.

244
00:20:48,553 --> 00:20:51,378
Just a momentary reminder of the impermanence of things.

245
00:20:52,340 --> 00:20:53,803
Relationships come to an end.

246
00:20:54,365 --> 00:20:55,867
Children leave the nest.

247
00:20:55,887 --> 00:20:56,849
The car breaks down.

248
00:20:57,590 --> 00:21:00,557
A ring, symbol of so many treasured memories, can be lost.

249
00:21:01,317 --> 00:21:02,580
A precious vase broken.

250
00:21:03,321 --> 00:21:06,147
Everything, everything comes to an end.

251
00:21:08,355 --> 00:21:11,742
But paradoxically, this doesn't make us gloomy, honestly.

252
00:21:12,644 --> 00:21:14,910
This doesn't lead to depression and despair.

253
00:21:15,892 --> 00:21:21,403
Not if we also contemplate the fact that at all times the universe is creating itself.

254
00:21:22,615 --> 00:21:27,063
that we will continue to recreate ourselves until we achieve liberation.

255
00:21:27,943 --> 00:21:29,066
This is the Buddha's teaching.

256
00:21:30,228 --> 00:21:40,826
He repeated over and over again to his critics and skeptics, I do not teach eternalism or annihilationism, but dependent co-arising.

257
00:21:41,988 --> 00:21:48,934
So it is, that death is never an end but a beginning, be it the end of a day, or year, or life.

258
00:21:50,155 --> 00:21:55,942
And this won't stop till the day of our death as Arahats, fully enlightened beings.

259
00:21:55,961 --> 00:22:08,433
That's why, after our little contemplation on sickness, old age and death in the evening, we go on to contemplate the enlightenment, the liberation, the awakening, the Buddha within, within us.

260
00:22:08,548 --> 00:22:10,853
That's what we're trying to bring into realization.

261
00:22:11,874 --> 00:22:25,894
And this balance of birth and death, appearance and disappearance, brings us to appreciate the preciousness of the very moment in which we live, the preciousness of that which exists and upon which our lives depend.

262
00:22:27,557 --> 00:22:31,022
Each present moment is to be received as a treasured present.

263
00:22:32,204 --> 00:22:37,492
So never mind a Ming vase, the old market crock is treated with gentle carefulness.

264
00:22:38,417 --> 00:22:47,811
If we can begin to treat things with this carefulness and gentility, how much more so living beings, human beings, my own being.

265
00:22:49,634 --> 00:22:56,064
For underlying all this change, all this birthing and dying, is something which neither is born nor dies.

266
00:22:56,965 --> 00:22:58,587
The Buddha is quite clear about this.

267
00:22:59,269 --> 00:23:03,935
There is an unborn, an undying, an uncompounded, an uncreated.

268
00:23:05,147 --> 00:23:15,833
And that's where we're trying to get to, to try and reach that deathless ground which exists right in the midst of all these fleeting phenomena and yet is untouched by it.

269
00:23:17,028 --> 00:23:38,849
That's the Buddha, walking about North India in the heat and the dust, going on arms rounds, talking to all sorts of people, some poor, some rich, some clever, some stupid, some powerful, high caste and low caste, all day long, mingling, a part of the world, affecting the world for the good.

270
00:23:38,829 --> 00:23:44,238
Yet within all that, the nirvanic peace, untouched by the exigencies of life.

271
00:23:45,480 --> 00:23:47,262
When he comes to die, he's still teaching.

272
00:23:48,223 --> 00:23:53,051
Finally, lying on his right side, he lets go of his decrepit, sick old body.

273
00:23:53,873 --> 00:23:54,653
Just like that.

274
00:23:55,736 --> 00:23:57,077
Easy-weezy-peasy.

275
00:23:57,638 --> 00:23:58,159
No fuss.

276
00:23:58,819 --> 00:23:59,361
No fear.

277
00:24:00,082 --> 00:24:00,923
Just letting go.

278
00:24:01,724 --> 00:24:02,526
Just going on.

279
00:24:04,480 --> 00:24:07,263
And that's exactly what we're learning to do in our meditation.

280
00:24:07,904 --> 00:24:12,590
We're learning to let everything go, allowing everything to arise and pass away.

281
00:24:12,651 --> 00:24:17,597
And that's exactly the purpose we observe impermanence in all its aspects.

282
00:24:19,259 --> 00:24:26,308
This impermanence, this transience as taught by the Buddha, isn't the change of one substance from one shape into another.

283
00:24:27,471 --> 00:24:34,200
It's not as though there's a piece of clay and we can mould it into a cup, screw it up and mould it into a saucer.

284
00:24:35,682 --> 00:24:40,952
That's what happens when we concentrate on the new and we see only the new arising out of the old.

285
00:24:41,854 --> 00:24:44,740
We suffer from this illusion of continuity.

286
00:24:46,463 --> 00:24:47,405
Just take this body.

287
00:24:48,227 --> 00:24:52,296
We've already said that every cell is replaced over a period of seven years.

288
00:24:53,116 --> 00:24:56,964
But it's all so slow that we don't perceive the process of change.

289
00:24:58,446 --> 00:25:01,810
But we also don't see the change so long as we are pleased by it.

290
00:25:02,692 --> 00:25:06,916
It's when those first wrinkles appear on the face or the hairline recedes a mite.

291
00:25:07,538 --> 00:25:09,500
Then, suddenly, we see change.

292
00:25:10,382 --> 00:25:11,923
Change in its darker aspect.

293
00:25:13,105 --> 00:25:15,027
That things are actually passing away.

294
00:25:16,209 --> 00:25:21,194
Just imagine if you got up one morning and looked in the mirror and saw someone else's face.

295
00:25:22,195 --> 00:25:23,557
Shock, horror, trauma.

296
00:25:24,558 --> 00:25:27,221
But at base, that's how discontinuous life is.

297
00:25:28,618 --> 00:25:30,863
The Buddha tells us there's radical change.

298
00:25:31,704 --> 00:25:36,193
What has come to be must collapse before what is to come can arise.

299
00:25:36,233 --> 00:25:41,463
That's the sort of level of insight we'd all like to get to in our meditation.

300
00:25:43,537 --> 00:25:52,748
One of our first insights is to see the transient nature of our body in the breath, of our emotions ballooning and deflating, of our thoughts flitting.

301
00:25:53,689 --> 00:26:00,757
And if we keep our investigation right there, acknowledging the arising and the falling, we begin to balance our view.

302
00:26:02,618 --> 00:26:06,163
Before we come to vipassana, we are aware of the new, the arising.

303
00:26:07,064 --> 00:26:10,387
Now we balance that with acknowledging the falling, the passing.

304
00:26:11,616 --> 00:26:15,480
There comes a time when we become more and more aware of the passing.

305
00:26:16,402 --> 00:26:20,146
We see quite distinctly that the world does really come to an end.

306
00:26:20,928 --> 00:26:24,751
It just breaks up, moment after moment.

307
00:26:24,771 --> 00:26:33,642
And if the insight into transience is to be developed rather than the other two characteristics of unsatisfactoriness and not-self or insubstantiality,

308
00:26:34,667 --> 00:26:47,849
then such a profound vision of the way things arise and pass away completely, moment after moment, will launch us into the first path and fruit of stream entra, the first level of spiritual liberation.

309
00:26:50,057 --> 00:26:58,788
Indeed, insight can come by observing impermanence at any level, whether at the microcosm of instants or the macrocosm of the stars.

310
00:26:59,829 --> 00:27:04,576
And that's what we really want, because with insight there comes a change of heart.

311
00:27:05,616 --> 00:27:11,744
There's a change in the deepest seat of our consciousness, a veritable turnaround.

312
00:27:11,724 --> 00:27:24,373
And that's what brings about not just a change of behaviour, but the purification which brings in its trail a deep sense of joy and purpose to our lives.

313
00:27:24,393 --> 00:27:28,823
The constant observation of transience will eventually get that penny to drop.

314
00:27:30,659 --> 00:27:51,070
Whether we observe it in the stars, the seasons, in the aging of the body, in the suddenness of death, or in the microcosmic world of moment-to-moment sensations, it will eventually begin to dawn on us, really dawn on us, that nothing, absolutely nothing, is worth holding on to.

315
00:27:52,031 --> 00:27:53,193
Not even for a moment.

316
00:27:54,236 --> 00:27:56,920
Not even for a nanosecond.

317
00:27:56,900 --> 00:27:57,461
Why?

318
00:27:58,201 --> 00:28:00,145
Because there's nothing there to hold on to.

319
00:28:00,205 --> 00:28:02,470
Like grasping water.

320
00:28:03,590 --> 00:28:05,114
Like grasping water.

321
00:28:07,258 --> 00:28:19,178
So it is that the contemplation of anicca, impermanence, in all its aspects, leads to an easy renunciation of trying to find happiness in a world of pleasure and pain.

322
00:28:20,473 --> 00:28:29,566
Samsara, the world of ever unquenchable searching, is this very relationship we have to the world out there and the world in here.

323
00:28:30,866 --> 00:28:39,759
Once we begin to let go of that unwholesome attachment, the world with all its pain and pleasure can't make us unhappy or happy.

324
00:28:40,900 --> 00:28:46,446
We've found that inner spiritual solitude and contentment that nothing can disturb.

325
00:28:48,789 --> 00:28:50,311
Let's pause here for a moment.

326
00:29:21,325 --> 00:29:32,346
So all we have to do is observe, just watch, whether it's the rising and falling of the abdomen, or the rising and falling of the foot, or any movement whatsoever.

327
00:29:33,288 --> 00:29:35,872
For there's always a beginning and an end.

328
00:29:36,913 --> 00:29:39,479
A beginning and an end, and nothing repeats itself.

329
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:43,586
What has arisen has gone, has arisen and gone for good.

330
00:29:45,186 --> 00:29:50,473
Let us have that faith in the higher faculty within us, satipaṇya.

331
00:29:50,493 --> 00:29:57,824
Let that intuitive intelligence do the work, get out of the way, just watch, just observe, and all will be revealed.

332
00:29:58,585 --> 00:29:59,685
It's as simple as that.

333
00:30:01,749 --> 00:30:06,455
The Buddha says in the Dhammapada, All conditioned things are impermanent.

334
00:30:07,217 --> 00:30:11,261
When we really see this, we become disenchanted with the world.

335
00:30:12,153 --> 00:30:17,859
Just this is the path that liberates us from all our suffering.

336
00:30:17,880 --> 00:30:24,448
Let me leave you with a more salutary note that so expresses for me the way an awakened being lives.

337
00:30:25,588 --> 00:30:28,011
William Blake, our homegrown mystical poet.

338
00:30:29,874 --> 00:30:35,300
He who binds to himself a joy does the winged life destroy.

339
00:30:36,541 --> 00:30:42,108
But he who kisses the joy as it flies lives in eternity's sunrise.

340
00:30:44,047 --> 00:30:58,303
May your profound insights into the characteristic of impermanence, anicca, allow such a depth of detachment that in an instant all dukkha, all unsatisfactoriness, will evaporate completely.

341
00:31:00,045 --> 00:31:11,116
May you all be fully liberated from the delusion of continuity and attain that unchanging nibbana sooner rather than later.
